3D Visualization in the Context of the Intersection between Data Visualization and Computer Vision

3D visualization is an important component at the intersection of Data Visualization and Computer Vision, as it enables the representation and analysis of spatial information derived from visual data. While computer vision focuses on extracting meaningful information from images and videos through computational methods, data visualization provides tools and techniques to present this information in a clear and interpretable way.
In general, 3D visualization refers to the graphical representation of data in three-dimensional space, typically using the axes x, y, and z. Unlike two-dimensional visualization, it allows the representation of depth and spatial relationships between objects. This is particularly important for analyzing real-world environments and structures that naturally exist in three dimensions.
Within computer vision, many algorithms aim to reconstruct or estimate the three-dimensional structure of scenes from images or sensor data. Techniques such as 3D reconstruction, depth estimation, and point cloud generation produce spatial datasets that require effective visualization methods for interpretation. 3D visualization tools allow researchers to explore these datasets interactively, examine spatial relationships, and evaluate the performance of computer vision models.
Such visualizations are widely used in applications including autonomous vehicles, robotics, medical imaging, and geographic mapping, where understanding spatial relationships between objects is essential. Therefore, 3D visualization plays a crucial role in transforming complex computational outputs into understandable visual representations, supporting both analysis and communication of results.
